{"id": "g28pee", "title": "REITs", "selftext": "**REIT total liabilities (REIT-L) are $1.3 trillion.**\n\nREIT-L as a percentage of all sector total liabilities is 2.8%. REIT-L as a percentage of nominal GDP is over 6%. No surprise, REIT-L and REIT performance (proxy: Wilshire REIT TMI) are correlated. I do not know the magic numbers here (i.e. what is *too* high of a %) but I will say that the explosion is REIT-L is something I'll watch *very* closely given recent and unfortunate events.\n\n&#x200B;\n\nhttps://preview.redd.it/eb9nrrjf64t41.png?width=896&format=png&auto=webp&s=a4e49dd2e13ac76a26c2d234a902f4b6f1f0ea41\n\nedit: since 2007 peak, REIT total liabilities have more than doubled.\n\nEdit 2: I should note that the previous events in real estate were not the same as what I am posting. Specifically, 2003-06 was about mortgage fraud/ liar loans. What this post is mainly concerned with is the concentration of capital (my perception) into REITs as an asset class, and why. Me thinks it\u2019s the reach for yield by yield starved investors since the GFC.", "created_utc": 1587014237.0, "permalink": "/r/wallstreetbets/comments/g28pee/reits/", "is_self": true}